Preheat your #oven{} to 200°C. Zest and halve the @lemon{1}. Roughly chop the @coriander{1}(stalks and all) and @flat leaf parsley{1}(stalks and all). Trim and coarsely grate the @carrot{1}(no need to peel). Drain and rinse the @chickpeas{1}. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}). Trim and thinly slice the @spring onion{2}.

Pop the carrot, lemon zest, chickpeas, coriander, half the parsley and half the spring onion in a large #bowl{}. Mix in the @plain flour{24}, @chermoula spice mix{1}, @mango chutney{40} and a pinch of @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch}. Squish together with your hands (or the back of a #fork{}) until the chickpeas are nicely broken up and mushy and the mixture sticks together. Keep to one side.

Chop the @sweet potato{2} into 2cm wide slices, then into 2cm wide chips. Pop on a #baking tray{}. Halve the @halloumi{250} lengthways, then chop each half lengthways into roughly four 2cm wide chip shape pieces. Drizzle the sweet potato with @oil{} and gently toss to coat. Roast in your oven until soft, ~{25%minutes}. Halfway through cooking, add the halloumi to the tray, turn the potatoes, then roast for the remaining time.

Shape the chickpea mix into five small balls per person. Flatten each ball gently to 2cm thick and pop on a #plate{}. Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a #frying pan{} on medium-high heat and then fry the patties in the hot oil until golden on both sides. This should take around ~{2-3%minutes} on each side. Transfer to a baking tray and pop onto the bottom shelf of your oven for ~{10-15%minutes}.

Meanwhile, quarter the @premium tomato mix{125}, pop them in a medium bowl. Add a glug of @olive oil{}, the remaining parsley, a squeeze of lemon juice and a pinch of @salt{pinch}, @pepper{pinch} and @sugar{pinch}. Mix and set aside. Trim the root from the @baby gem lettuce{1} then half lengthways. Thinly slice widthways. Put the @Greek style natural yoghurt{150} in a bowl and add the garlic (add less if you don't love raw garlic) and a pinch of @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch} and a splash of @water{}. Mix to a drizzling consistency.

Pop the @plain naans{2} in your oven for the last ~{4-5%minutes} of chip's cooking time. Add three-quarters of the yoghurt to the tomatoes along with the baby gem lettuce and gently combine. Serve the naans with the salad on top, then the falafels. Serve the sweet potato and halloumi chips on the side. Drizzle the remaining yoghurt over the chips and then sprinkle on the @za'atar{1} and remaining spring onion. Cut any remaining lemon into wedges to serve. Enjoy!

> The perfect recipe for sharing with friends, our herby falafel flatbreads are home-made, quick and fun to make, plus preparing it from scratch tastes even better!